SIMPLE: torpedo
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Torpedo
<hw>Tor*pe"do</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Torpedoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>torpedo</ets>,
<ets>-inis</ets>, from <ets>torpere</ets> to be stiff, numb, or torpid.
See <er>Torpid</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of
elasmobranch fishes belonging to <gen>Torpedo</gen> and allied genera.
They are related to the rays, but have the power of giving electrical
shocks. Called also <altname>crampfish</altname>, and
<altname>numbfish</altname>. See <cref>Electrical fish</cref>, under
<er>Electrical</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The common European torpedo (<spn>Torpedo
vulgaris</spn>) and the American species (<spn>Torpedo
occidentalis</spn>) are the best known.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An engine or machine for destroying ships by blowing
them up; a mine{4}.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>A quantity of explosives anchored in a channel,
beneath the water, or set adrift in a current, and so designed that they
will explode when touched or approached by a vessel, or when an electric
circuit is closed by an operator on shore; now called <altname>marine
mine</altname>.</def> <mark>[obsolete]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Damn the <qex>torpedoes</qex> -- full speed ahead!</q>
<rj><qau>Adm. David Glasgow Farragut (At the battle of Mobile Bay,
1864).</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A kind of small submarine boat carrying an
explosive charge, and projected from a ship against another ship at a
distance, or made self-propelling, and otherwise automatic in its action
against a distant ship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A kind of shell or cartridge
buried in earth, to be exploded by electricity or by stepping on it; now
called <altname>land mine</altname>.</def> <mark>[obsolete]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Railroad)</fld> <def>A kind of detonating cartridge
or shell placed on a rail, and exploded when crushed under the
locomotive wheels, -- used as an alarm signal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An explosive cartridge or shell lowered or dropped
into a bored oil well, and there exploded, to clear the well of
obstructions or to open communication with a source of supply of
oil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A kind of firework in the form of a small ball, or
pellet, which explodes when thrown upon a hard object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>An automobile with a <er>torpedo body</er>.</def>
<mark>[Archaic Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fish torpedo</b></col>, <cd>a spindle-shaped, or
fish-shaped, self-propelling submarine torpedo.</cd> -- <col><b>Spar
torpedo</b></col>, <cd>a canister or other vessel containing an
explosive charge, and attached to the end of a long spar which projects
from a ship or boat and is thrust against an enemy's ship, exploding the
torpedo.</cd> -- <col><b>Torpedo boat</b></col>, <cd>a vessel adapted
for carrying, launching, operating, or otherwise making use of,
torpedoes against an enemy's ship., especially, a small, fast boat with
tubes for launching torpedoes.</cd> -- <col><b>Torpedo
nettings</b></col>, <cd>nettings made of chains or bars, which can be
suspended around a vessel and allowed to sink beneath the surface of the
water, as a protection against torpedoes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torpedo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Torpedo
<hw>Tor*pe"do</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>to destroy by, or
subject to the action of, a torpedo.</def> <rj><au>London
Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>[Fig.]</mark> <def>To destroy, cause to halt, or
prevent from being accomplished; -- used esp. with reference to a plan
or an enterprise, halted by some action before the plan is put into
execution.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torpedo-boat destroyer</ent>⟦br⟧
